'''Nishoyamada Shrine''' (二所山田神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Shūnan, Yamaguchi|ja|周南市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Yamaguchi Prefecture|ja|山口県|12=draft}}, Japan. It is listed as a {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=draft}} and was formerly Ranked as a {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|12=draft}} under the Modern shrine Ranking system.

The shrine was established through the merger of Nisho Shrine and Yamada Shrine during the Meiji period. The deities enshrined at the former Nisho Shrine are {{ill|Yachihoko|ja|八千矛神|12=draft}} and {{ill|Ōmononushi|ja|大物主神|12=draft}}, while those of the former Yamada Shrine are {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|12=draft}} and {{ill|Toyouke-Ōmikami|ja|豊受大神|lt=Toyouke Ōmikami|1=Toyouke-hime|12=draft}}.

The shrine operates a monthly publication called "Joshi-dō-sha" (女子道社), which manufactures approximately 70% of the {{ill|Omikuji|ja|おみくじ|12=draft}} distributed at shrines and temples throughout Japan.

== History ==
Nisho Shrine, originally known as "Nisho Daimyōjin," is said to have been founded in 899 (Shōtai 2) according to shrine tradition. A record from 1262 (Kōchō 2) refers to it as "Nisho Futamata Shrine," and it is considered one of the possible sites of the "Futamata Shrine" listed in the {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|12=draft}} for {{ill|Suō Province|ja|周防国|12=draft}}'s Tō District, alongside two other candidate shrines. The shrine was supported by the {{ill|Ōuchi clan|ja|大内氏|12=draft}}, who constructed shrine buildings in 1321 (Genkō 1), and designated as a place of prayer by the {{ill|Mōri clan|ja|毛利氏|12=draft}}. In the early Meiji period, it was Ranked as a Gōsha.

Yamada Shrine, formerly called "Yamada Gonzen-sha," is said to have been founded following a deity transfer from Yamada in {{ill|Ise Province|ja|伊勢国|12=draft}}. It is mentioned in the {{ill|Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku|ja|日本文徳天皇実録|12=draft}}, entry for June 23, 878 (Gangyō 2), as "Yamada Shrine of Akada, Suō Province," making it a {{ill|Kokushi genzaisha|ja|国史見在社|12=draft}}. However, another Yamada Shrine in {{ill|Suo-Oshima, Yamaguchi|ja|周防大島町|12=draft}} is also considered a candidate for this historical reference. Yamada Shrine was Ranked as a Village Shrine in the early Meiji period.

In 1907 (Meiji 40), Nisho Shrine and Yamada Shrine merged to form the present Nishoyamada Shrine.

During the Meiji period, the shrine's chief priest, Miyamoto Shigetane, established the nationwide women's organization "Greater Japan Respect-for-the-Deities Women's Association" (大日本敬神婦人会) to promote women's independence. In 1906 (Meiji 39), he launched the association’s magazine, ''Joshi-dō'' (女子道), and began manufacturing {{ill|Omikuji|ja|おみくじ|12=draft}} as a source of funding. Today, the shrine's affiliated organization produces about 70% of all omikuji in Japan and even developed the first omikuji vending machines.

